          fisheye-type lenses

attribute.title: calibration_source_id
attribute.description: The calibration_source_id is used to identify the source used in calibrating the instrument.

attribute.title: model_type
attribute.description: The model_type attribute specifies an identifier for the type or kind of model. The value should be one of a well defined set, providing an application program with sufficient information to know how to handle the rest of the parameters within the model. This value will correlate directly with the specific camera model class that is a subclass of the Camera_Model_Parameters class.

attribute.title: solution_id
attribute.description: The solution_id attribute specifies the unique identifier for the solution set to which the values in the group belong. For certain kinds of information, such as pointing correction (pointing models) and rover localization (coordinate system definitions), the "true" value is unknown and only estimates of the true value exist. Thus, more than one set of estimates may exist simultaneously, each valid for its intended purpose. Each of these sets is called a "solution" to the unknown true value. The solution_id attribute is used to identify which solution is being expressed by the containing group. No specific naming convention is defined here, however it is recommended that projects adopt one. The intent is to be able to identify who created the solution, and why. Possible components of the naming convention include user, institution, purpose, request ID, version, program, date/time. The value is not case-sensitive.

attribute.title: positive_azimuth_direction
attribute.description: The positive_azimuth_direction attribute specifies the direction in which azimuth is measured in positive degrees for an observer on the surface of a body. The azimuth is measured with respect to the elevational reference plane. A value of CW indicates that azimuth is measured positively Clockwise, and CCW indicates that azimuth increases positively Counter-clockwise.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Indicates that azimuth is measured positively Clockwise.
Indicates that azimuth is measured positively Counter-clockwise.
Indicates that azimuth is measured positively Clockwise.
Indicates that azimuth is measured positively Counter-clockwise.

attribute.title: positive_elevation_direction
attribute.description: The positive_elevation_direction attribute provides the direction in which elevation is measured in positive degrees for an observer on the surface of a body. The elevation is measured with respect to the azimuthal reference plane. A value of UP or ZENITH indicates that elevation is measured positively upwards, i.e., the zenith point would be at +90 degrees and the nadir point at -90 degrees. DOWN or NADIR indicates that the elevation is measured positively downwards; the zenith point would be at -90 degrees and the nadir point at +90 degrees.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning:

attribute.title: coordinate_system_time
attribute.description: The coordinate_system_time provides the instantiation time for the coordinate system.

attribute.title: coordinate_system_type
attribute.description: The coordinate_system_type distinguishes between options such as rectangular, spherical, planetocentric, etc.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: The coordinate system uses rectangular coordinates.

The coordinate system uses azimuth-elevation coordinates. 
                  Azimuth: angle from +X axis to projection of position vector on x-y 
                  plane increases in clockwise direction (-180 to +180).
                  Elevation: angle between position vector and x-y plane (-90 to +90).

The coordinate system uses spherical coordinates.
                  Longitude: angle from +X axis to projection of position vector on 
                  X-Y plane increases in clockwise direction (0 to 360).
                  Colatitude: angle between +Z axis and position vector (0 to 180).

The coordinate system uses planetocentric coordinates. 
                    Planetocentric longitude increases positively eastward (-180 to +180).
                    Planetocentric latitude increases positively northward (-90 to +90).
                    For planets and their satellites the +Z axis (+90 latitude) always 
                  points to the north side of the invariable plane (the plane whose 
                  normal vector is the angular momentum vector of the solar system).
                    For dwarf planets, asteroids and comets the IAU defines their positive 
                    pole such that their spin is in the right hand sense about 
                    their positive pole. The positive pole may point above or below the 
                    invariable plane of the solar system. This revision by the IAU Working 
                    Group (2006) inverts what had been the direction of the north pole for 
                    Pluto, Charon and Ida.

The coordinate system uses planetodetic coordinates.
                   For planets and their satellites the +Z axis (+90 latitude) always 
                   points to the north side of the invariable plane (the plane whose 
                   normal vector is the angular momentum vector of the solar system).
                   Planetodetic longitude increases positively eastward (-180 to +180).
                   Planetodetic latitude is tied to a reference ellipsoid. For a point, 
                   P, on a reference ellipsoid, angle measured from X-Y plane to the 
                   surface normal at the point of interest. For other points, equals 
                   latitude at the nearest point on the reference ellipsoid. Increases 
                   positively northward (-90 to +90).

The coordinate system uses planetographic coordinates. 
                  For planet and satellite planetographic coordinate systems: 
                  Planetographic longitude is usually defined such that the sub-observer 
                  longitude increases with time as seen by a distant, fixed observer 
                  (0 to 360). The earth, moon and sun are exceptions; planetographic 
                  longitude is positive east by default (0 to 360). Planetographic 
                  latitude is planetodetic latitude (-90 to +90).
                  For dwarf planets, asteroids and comets: there are multiple, inconsistent 
                  standards. Currently, for these objects, PDS permits planetographic 
                  coordinates to be provided in addition to, not in lieu of, either 
                  planetocentric or planetodetic coordinates.

attribute.title: emission_angle
attribute.description: The emission_angle element provides the value of the angle between the surface normal vector at the intercept point and a vector from the intercept point to the spacecraft. The emission_angle varies from 0 degrees when the spacecraft is viewing the subspacecraft point (nadir viewing) to 90 degrees when the intercept is tangent to the surface of the target body. Thus, higher values of emission_angle indicate more oblique viewing of the target. Values in the range of 90 to 180 degrees are possible for ring data.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: incidence_angle
attribute.description: The incidence_angle element provides a measure of the lighting condition at the intercept point. Incidence angle is the angle between the local vertical at the intercept point (surface) and a vector from the intercept point to the sun. The incidence_angle varies from 0 degrees when the intercept point coincides with the subsolar point to 90 degrees when the intercept point is at the terminator (i.e., in the shadowed or dark portion of the target body). Thus, higher values of incidence_angle indicate the existence of a greater number of surface shadows. Note: In PDS labels for Magellan's altimetry and radiometry products, and for Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter Mini-RF products, incidence_angle is defined as the value of the angle between the local vertical and the spacecraft direction. For Magellan this is measured at the center of the radiometer footprint at rad_spacecraft_epoch_time.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: instrument_azimuth
attribute.description: The instrument_azimuth attribute specifies the value for an instrument's rotation in the horizontal direction. It is usually measured from some kind of low hard stop. Although it may be used for any instrument where it makes sense, it is primarily intended for use in surface-based instruments that measure pointing in terms of azimuth and elevation. When in a group, defines the azimuth (horizontal rotation) at which the instrument is pointed. This value is expressed using the coordinate system referred to by REFERENCE_COORD_SYSTEM_NAME and REFERENCE_COORD_SYSTEM_INDEX contained within the same group. The interpretation of exactly what part of the instrument is being pointed is mission-specific. It could be the boresight, the camera head direction, the CAHV camera model A vector direction, or any of a number of other things. As such, for multimission use this value should be used mostly as an approximation, e.g. identifying scenes which might contain a given object.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: instrument_elevation
attribute.description: The instrument_elevation attribute specifies the value for an instrument's rotation in the vertical direction. It is usually measured from some kind of low hard stop. Although it may be used for any instrument where it makes sense, it is primarily intended for use in surface-based instruments that measure pointing in terms of azimuth and elevation. When in a group, defines the elevation (vertical rotation) at which the instrument is pointed. This value is expressed using the coordinate system referred to by REFERENCE_COORD_SYSTEM_NAME and REFERENCE_COORD_SYSTEM_INDEX contained within the same group. The interpretation of exactly what part of the instrument is being pointed is mission-specific. It could be the boresight, the camera head direction, the CAHV camera model A vector direction, or any of a number of other things. As such, for multimission use this value should be used mostly as an approximation, e.g. identifying scenes which might contain a given object.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: phase_angle
attribute.description: The phase_angle element provides a measure of the relationship between the instrument viewing position and incident illumination (such as solar light). Phase_angle is measured at the target; it is the angle between a vector to the illumination source and a vector to the instrument. If not specfied, the target is assumed to be at the center of the instrument field of view. If illumination is from behind the instrument, phase_angle will be small.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: solar_azimuth
attribute.description: The solar_azimuth attribute specifies one of two angular measurements indicating the direction to the Sun as measured from a specific point on the surface of a planet (ex., from a lander or rover). The positive direction of the elevation is set by the positive_azimuth_direction attribute in the reference coordinate space. The azimuth is measured positively in the clockwise direction (as viewed from above) with the meridian passing through the positive spin axis of the planet (i.e., the north pole) defining the zero reference.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: solar_elevation
attribute.description: The solar_elevation attribute specifies one of two angular measurements indicating the direction to the Sun as measured from a specific point on the surface of a planet (ex., from a lander or rover). The positive direction of the elevation is set by the positive_elevation_direction attribute in the reference coordinate space. The elevation is measured from the plane which is normal to the line passing between the surface point and the planet's center of mass, and which intersects the surface point.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: start_azimuth
attribute.description: The start_azimuth attribute specifies the angular distance from a fixed reference position at which an image or observation starts. Azimuth is measured in a spherical coordinate system, in a plane normal to the principal axis. Azimuth values increase according to the right hand rule relative to the positive direction of the principal axis of the spherical coordinate system. When applied to a site or surface projection coordinate space, specifies the azimuth of the left edge of the output map. Applies to Cylindrical and Cylindrical-Perspective projections only.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: stop_azimuth
attribute.description: The stop_azimuth attribute specifies the angular distance from a fixed reference position at which an image or observation stops. Azimuth is measured in a spherical coordinate system, in a plane normal to the principal axis. Azimuth values increase according to the right hand rule relative to the positive direction of the principal axis of the spherical coordinate system. When applied to a site or surface projection coordinate space, specifies the azimuth of the right edge of the output map. Applies to Cylindrical and Cylindrical-Perspective projections only.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: body_positive_pole_clock_angle
attribute.description: The body_positive_pole_clock_angle element specifies the direction of a body's rotation axis in an image. This attribute typically is used when specifying body center coorinates for dwarf planets, minor planets, their satellites, and for comets. It is measured from the 'upward' direction in the image, clockwise to the direction of the positive rotational pole as projected into the image plane, assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class. The positive pole is used to define the poles of dwarf planets, minor planets, their satellites, and comets according to the right-hand rule. "positive" is the pole toward which the thumb points when the fingers are curled in the body's direction of rotation.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: celestial_north_clock_angle
attribute.description: The celestial_north_clock_angle attribute specifies the direction of celestial north at the center of an image. It is measured from the 'upward' direction, clockwise to the direction toward celestial north, assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class..
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: central_body_north_pole_clock_angle
attribute.description: The central_body_north_pole_clock_angle element specifies the direction of the central body's (e.g., planet's)rotation axis in an image. It is measured from the 'upward' direction in the image, clockwise to the direction of the northern rotational pole as projected into the image plane, assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class. The north pole of a planet or any of its satellites in the solar system is the pole of the rotation axis that is in the same celestial hemisphere relative to the invariable plane of the solar system as Earth's North pole.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: ecliptic_north_clock_angle
attribute.description: The ecliptic_north_clock_angle attribute specifies the direction of ecliptic north at the center of an image. It is measured from the 'upward' direction, clockwise to the direction toward ecliptic north, assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class..
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: sun_direction_clock_angle
attribute.description: The sun_direction_clock_angle attribute specifies the direction of the sun as an angle measured from a line 'upward' from the center of the field of view, clockwise to the direction toward sun, assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class..
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: target_north_pole_clock_angle
attribute.description: The target_north_pole_clock_angle element specifies the direction of the target body's rotation axis in an image. It is measured from the 'upward' direction in the image, clockwise to the direction of the northern rotational pole as projected into the image plane, assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class. The north pole of a planet or any of its satellites in the solar system is the pole of the rotation axis that is in the same celestial hemisphere relative to the invariable plane of the solar system as Earth's North pole.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: target_positive_pole_clock_angle
attribute.description: The target_positive_pole_clock_angle element specifies the direction of the target body's rotation axis in an image. It is measured from the 'upward' direction in the image, clockwise to the direction of the positive rotational pole as projected into the image plane, assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class. The positive pole is used to define the poles of dwarf planets, minor planets, their satellites, and comets according to the right-hand rule. "positive" is the pole toward which the thumb points when the fingers are curled in the body's direction of rotation.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: east_azimuth
attribute.description: Assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class, the east_azimuth attribute provides the value of the angle between a line from the image center to the east and a reference line in the image plane. The reference line is a horizontal line from the image center to the middle right edge of the image. This angle increases in a clockwise direction.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: north_azimuth
attribute.description: Assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class, the north_azimuth attribute provides the value of the angle between a line from the image center to the north pole and a reference line in the image plane. The reference line is a horizontal line from the image center to the middle right edge of the image. This angle increases in a clockwise direction.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: celestial_north_clock_angle
attribute.description: The celestial_north_clock_angle attribute specifies the direction of celestial north at the center of an image. It is measured from the 'upward' direction, clockwise to the direction toward celestial north, assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class..
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: declination_angle
attribute.description: The declination_angle (Dec) attribute provides the value of an angle on the celestial sphere, measured north from the celestial equator to the point in question. (For points south of the celestial equator, negative values are used.) declination is used in conjunction with the right_ascension attribute to specify a point on the sky.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: ecliptic_north_clock_angle
attribute.description: The ecliptic_north_clock_angle attribute specifies the direction of ecliptic north at the center of an image. It is measured from the 'upward' direction, clockwise to the direction toward ecliptic north, assuming the image is displayed as defined by the Display_Direction class..
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: geometry_reference_time

attribute.title: right_ascension_angle
attribute.description: The right_ascension_angle attribute provides the value of right ascension (RA) as an angle. Right ascension is measured from the vernal equinox or the first point of Aries, which is the place on the celestial sphere where the Sun crosses the celestial equator from south to north at the March equinox. Right ascension is measured continuously in a full circle from that equinox towards the east. Right ascension is used in conjunction with the declination attribute to specify a point on the sky.Note Right Ascension is normally given in hour angles in which case the appropriate attribute is right_ascension_hour_angle.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: right_ascension_hour_angle
attribute.description: The right_ascension_hour_angle attribute provides the value of right ascension (RA) as in terms of hour angles (hh:mm:ss.sss...). Right ascension is measured from the vernal equinox or the first point of Aries, which is the place on the celestial sphere where the Sun crosses the celestial equator from south to north at the March equinox. Right ascension is measured continuously in a full circle from that equinox towards the east. Right ascension is used in conjunction with the declination attribute to specify a point on the sky.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: horizontal_pixel_scale_factor

attribute.title: latitude_position

Latitudes are defined to be positive in the northern (as defined by the IAU) hemisphere.

attribute.title: rotation_direction
attribute.description: The rotation_direction attribute identifies the direction of the rotation for a specific quaternion. This is used when the two frames involved are unambiguously identifed in the enclosing classes.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning:
The quaternion rotates the frame identifed by 
                  Present_Coordinate_Space to the frame identified by
                  Reference_Coordinate_Space.

The quaternion rotates the frame identifed by 
                  Reference_Coordinate_Space to the frame identified by
                  Present_Coordinate_Space.

Reference frames are generally defined sequentially 
                  from a base reference frame (e.g., base frames might be ICRF, IAU 
                  Mars, or the the landing site from which a rover begins its exploration).
                  rotation_direction = Forward corresponds to rotation in the 'direction' 
                  from the base frame.

Reference frames are generally defined sequentially 
                  from a base reference frame (e.g., base frames might be ICRF, IAU

attribute.title: qcos
attribute.description: qcos is the scalar component of a quaternion. qcos = cos(theta/2), where theta is the angle of rotation.

attribute.title: qsin1
attribute.description: qsin1 is the first element of the vector component of a quaternion. qsin1 = x*sin(theta/2) where theta is the angle of rotation and (x,y,z) is the unit vector around which the rotation occurs.

attribute.title: qsin2
attribute.description: qsin2 is the second element of the vector component of a quaternion. qsin2 = y*sin(theta/2) where theta is the angle of rotation and (x,y,z) is the unit vector around which the rotation occurs.

attribute.title: qsin3
attribute.description: qsin3 is the third element of the vector component of a quaternion. qsin3 = z*sin(theta/2) where theta is the angle of rotation and (x,y,z) is the unit vector around which the rotation occurs.

attribute.title: auto_exposure_data_cut
attribute.description: The auto_exposure_data_cut element provides the DN value which a specified fraction of pixels is permitted to exceed. The fraction is specified using the auto_exposure_pixel_fraction keyword.

attribute.title: auto_exposure_percent
attribute.description: The auto_exposure_percent specifies the auto-exposure early-termination percent. If the calculated exposure time has written this value, then terminate auto exposure early.

attribute.title: auto_exposure_pixel_fraction
attribute.description: The auto_exposure_pixel_fraction attribute provides the percentage of pixels whose value is higher than the auto_exposure_data_cut keyword. Note: For Mars Pathfinder, this field is only applicable if the exposure type is set to AUTO or INCREMENTAL.

attribute.title: command_sequence_number
attribute.description: The command_sequence_number attribute provides a numeric identifier for a sequence of commands sent to a spacecraft or instrument.

attribute.title: detector_erase_count
attribute.description: The detector_erase_count specifies the number of times a detector has been flushed of data in raw counts.

attribute.title: exposure_duration_count
attribute.description: The exposure_duration_count attribute specifies the value, in raw counts, of the time interval between the opening and closing of an instrument aperture (such as a camera shutter). This is a raw value taken directly from telemetry, as opposed to the exposure_duration attribute, which has been converted to engineering units. For ChemCam on MSL, it is the exposure time for manual exposure and seed time for auto exposure of the RMI.

attribute.title: exposure_type
attribute.description: The exposure_type attribute indicates the exposure setting on a camera.

attribute.title: max_auto_exposure_iteration_count
attribute.description: The max_auto_exposure_iteration_count specifies the maximum number of exposure iterations the instrument will perform in order to obtain the requested exposure when operating in an autonomous mode.

attribute.title: description
attribute.description: The description attribute provides a statement, picture in words, or account that describes or is otherwise relevant to the object.

attribute.title: name
attribute.description: The name attribute provides a word or combination of words by which the object is known.

attribute.title: data_correction_subtype
attribute.description: The data_correction_subtype attribute specifies the specific type of data correction to be applied within the realm of the accompanying data_correction_type.

attribute.title: data_correction_type
attribute.description: The data_correction_type attribute specifies the type of data correction to be applied using the accompanying file.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning:
The accompanying referenced file contains brightness correction parameters
          for each input file to the derived product. Brightness correction is defined as a mosaic
          radiometric seam matching process that is done on top of ordinary radiometric correction.
          Its intent is to reduce visual seams at the expense of radiometric
          accuracy.

The accompanying data_correction_file should be used to perform radiometric
          calibration of the image. The dark current image provides a reference label of the
          build-up of any charges on the sensor that need to be subtracted from a shuttered image
          during calibration. Selection of the appropriate dark current image may be based on time,
          camera, temperature, readout conditions, light flood, gain and offset.

Used to perform radiometric calibration of the image, the flat field image
          provides a reference label of the sensitivity of the used optics across the field of view.
          The shuttered image needs to be divided by the flat field image during calibration.
          Selection of the appropriate flat field image may be based on time, camera, temperature,
          readout conditions, light flood, gain and offset.

Specifies the name of the inverse-lookup-table file used in generating the
          RDR. NOTE: This keyword only applies if sample_bit_mode_id attribute starts with "LUT", i.e. if an
          inverse lookup table file was used.

Specifies the name of the responsivity constants file used in generating the RDR
          used to correct for distortion due to temperature.

attribute.title: description
attribute.description: The description attribute provides a statement, picture in words, or account that describes or is otherwise relevant to the object.

attribute.title: antiblooming_state_flag
attribute.description: The antiblooming_state_flag attribute indicates whether antiblooming was used for this image. Blooming occurs when photons from an individual cell in a CCD array overflow into surrounding cells. Antiblooming measures are used to either prevent or correct for this effect.

attribute.title: bad_pixel_replacement_flag
attribute.description: The bad_pixel_replacement_flag attribute indicates whether or not bad pixel replacement processing was completed. Note: For MPF, if set to TRUE, certain pixels in the image were replaced based on a bad pixel table.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: null
null

attribute.title: blemish_protection_flag
attribute.description: The blemish_protection_flag attribute indicates whether the blemish protection was on or off.

attribute.title: dark_current_correction_flag
attribute.description: The dark_current_correction_flag attribute indicates whether or not a dark current correction was applied to an image. Note: For MPF, this correction was applied to the image on board the spacecraft, before the image was transmitted to Earth.

attribute.title: flat_field_correction_flag
attribute.description: The flat_field_correction_flag attribute indicates whether or not a flat field correction was applied to an image.

attribute.title: gain_mode_id
attribute.description: The gain_mode_id attribute identifies the gain state of an instrument. Gain is a constant value which is multiplied with an instrument's output signal to increase or decrease the level of that output.

attribute.title: geometry_projection_type
attribute.description: The geometry_projection_type attribute specifies the state of the pixels in an image before a re-projection has been applied. Describes if or how the pixels have been reprojected. RAW indicates reprojection has not been done; the pixels are as they came from the camera. Other types are defined by missions.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Indicates the image uses a CAHVOR or one of the CAHVORE camera models.
Indicates reprojection has been performed to linearize the camera model (thus removing things like lens distortion). This means the image uses a CAHV camera model.

attribute.title: light_flood_state_flag
attribute.description: The light_flood_state_flag attribute indicates the mode (on or off) of light flooding for an instrument.

attribute.title: offset_mode_id
attribute.description: The offset_mode_id attribute identifies the analog value that is subtracted from the video signal prior to the analog/digital converters.

attribute.title: responsivity_constant
attribute.description: The shutter_correction_mode_id attribute specifies a responsivity constant used in generating the RDR.

attribute.title: shutter_correction_mode_id
attribute.description: The shutter_correction_mode_id attribute specifies whether shutter subtraction will be performed.

attribute.title: shutter_effect_correction_flag
attribute.description: The shutter_effect_correction_flag attribute indicates whether or not a shutter effect correction was applied to the image. The shutter effect correction involves the removal from the image of the shutter, or fixed-pattern.

attribute.title: derived_image_type
attribute.description: The derived_image_type attribute specifies how to interpret the pixel values in a derived image RDR (or colloquially, the type of the derived image itself). Valid values vary per mission.

attribute.title: horizon_mask_elevation
attribute.description: The horizon_mask_elevation attribute specifies the elevation (in degrees) used as the horizontal cutoff in a mask file that, when applied to another image file, prevents the horizon and sky features in the image from being processed. If this keyword is not present in the product label, no horizon mask was used.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: crosstrack_summing
attribute.description: The crosstrack_summing attribute provides the number of detector pixel values in the crosstrack direction that have been averaged to produce the final output pixel.

attribute.title: downtrack_summing
attribute.description: The downtrack_summing attribute provides the number of detector pixel values in the downtrack direction that have been averaged to produce the final output pixel.

attribute.title: pixel_averaging_height
attribute.description: The pixel_averaging_height attribute provides the vertical dimension, in pixels, of the area over which pixels were averaged prior to image compression.

attribute.title: pixel_averaging_width
attribute.description: The pixel_averaging_width attribute provides the horizontal dimension, in pixels, of the area over which pixels were averaged prior to image compression.

attribute.title: center_filter_wavelength
attribute.description: The center_filter_wavelength attribute provides the mid_point wavelength value between the minimum and maximum instrument filter wavelength values.
attribute.unitId: AU, Angstrom, cm, km, m, micrometer, mm, nm

attribute.title: filter_id
attribute.description: The filter_id attribute provides a short string identifier for an instrument filter through which an image or measurement was acquired or which is associated with a given instrument mode.

attribute.title: filter_name
attribute.description: The filter_name attribute provides the commonly-used name of the instrument filter through which an image or measurement was acquired or which is associated with a given instrument mode.

attribute.title: filter_number
attribute.description: The filter_number attribute provides the numeric identifier of an instrument filter through which an image or measurement was acquired or which is associated with a given instrument mode. Within the bin class of a spectral data object, it identifies the filter through which data in the given band were acquired.

attribute.title: full_width_half_maximum
attribute.description: The full_width_half_maximum attribute describes the width of a "bump" on a curve or function. It is given by the distance between points on the curve at which the function reaches half of its maximum value.
attribute.unitId: AU, Angstrom, cm, km, m, micrometer, mm, nm

attribute.title: comment
attribute.description: The comment attribute is a character string expressing one or more remarks or thoughts relevant to the object.

attribute.title: linearization_mode
attribute.description: The linearization_mode attribute specifies what kind of stereo partner was used to linearize the image (the process requires two camera models).

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning:
The image was linearized using the nominal stereo partner at the same
          pointing (whether or not the partner image was actually acquired).

The image was linearized using an actual stereo partner image, which may be
          at a different pointing or rover location (e.g. long-baseline or re-pointed stereo). The
          actual partner product will be referenced by the Stereo_Product_Reference
          class.
Linearization has not been performed.

attribute.title: linearization_mode_fov
attribute.description: The linearization_mode_fov attribute specifies how the linearized camera model's field of view (FOV) w as constructed (corresponding to the "cahv_fov" parameter in MIPL software).

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning:
Indicates the FOV is the intersection of the two cameras, which means some
          data are cut off and typically stretched horizontally, but there are no black
          areas.

Indicates the FOV is the union of the two cameras, which preserves the edges
          of the images but typically compresses the image horizontally, and creates black
          areas.

Uses only the CAHV vectors, which tends to preserve the aspect ratio and
          scale of the original but both cuts off data and has black areas.
Linearization has not been performed.

attribute.title: azimuth_fov
attribute.description: The azimuth_fov attribute specifies the angular measure of the horizontal field of view of an imaged scene.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: bayer_mode
attribute.description: The bayer_mode attribute specifies whether or not the data is encoded in a Bayer pattern, and if not, how the pattern was removed.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Image was never Bayer encoded
Raw Bayer-encoded data from the CCD

Bayer pattern removed onboard to produce full-resolution color (using Malvar
          algorithm)
Debayering by MIPL using Malvar algorithm.

attribute.title: detector_to_image_rotation
attribute.description: The detector_to_image_rotation attribute specifies the clockwise rotation, in degrees, that was applied to an image along its optical path through an instrument, from detector to final image orientation.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: elevation_fov
attribute.description: The elevation_fov attribute specifies the angular measure of the vertical field of view of an imaged scene.
attribute.unitId: arcmin, arcsec, deg, hr, mrad, rad

attribute.title: exposure_count
attribute.description: The exposure count attribute provides the maximum number of exposures taken during a specified interval. The value is dependent on exposure type.

attribute.title: exposure_duration
attribute.description: The exposure_duration attribute provides the value of the time interval between the opening and closing of an instrument aperture (such as a camera shutter).
attribute.unitId: day, hr, julian day, microseconds, min, ms, s, yr

attribute.title: exposure_duration_count
attribute.description: The exposure_duration_count attribute specifies the value, in raw counts, of the time interval between the opening and closing of an instrument aperture (such as a camera shutter). This is a raw value taken directly from telemetry, as opposed to the exposure_duration attribute, which has been converted to engineering units. For ChemCam on MSL, it is the exposure time for manual exposure and seed time for auto exposure of the RMI.

attribute.title: first_line
attribute.description: The first_line attribute indicates the line within a source image that corresponds to the first line in a sub-image.

attribute.title: first_sample
attribute.description: The first_sample attribute indicates the sample within a source image that corresponds to the first sample in a sub-image.

attribute.title: frame_id
attribute.description: The frame_id attribute provides an identification for a particular instrument measurement frame. A frame consists of a sequence of measurements made over a specified time interval, and may include measurements from different instrument modes. These sequences repeat from cycle to cycle and sometimes within a cycle.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Left frame transmitted to Earth
Right frame transmitted to Earth
Applies when non-stereo image is taken with no left or right designator

attribute.title: frame_type
attribute.description: The frame_type attribute specifies whether the image was commanded as part of a stereo pair or as a single left or right monoscopic image. If frame_type=STEREO, a left and a right image should be present for the same image_id.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: image was commanded as a single left or right monoscopic image
image was commanded as part of a stereo pair

attribute.title: instrument_mode_id
attribute.description: The instrument_mode_id element provides an instrument-dependent designation of operating mode. This may be simply a number, letter or code, or a word such as 'normal', 'full resolution', 'near encounter', or 'fixed grating'.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Applies when non-stereo image is taken with no left or right designator

attribute.title: sample_bit_method
attribute.description: The sample_bit_method attribute specifies the method in which bit scaling is performed.

attribute.title: sample_bit_mode_id
attribute.description: The sample_bit_mode_id attribute specifies the type of pixel scaling performed.

attribute.title: ac_quantization_table_id
attribute.description: The ac_quantization_table_id attribute provides the index used to select the JPEG AC-Huffman Luminance Bits lookup table for compression.

attribute.title: dc_quantization_table_id
attribute.description: The dc_quantization_table_id attribute provides the index used to select the JPEG DC-Huffman Luminance Bits lookup table for compression.

attribute.title: decomposition_stages
attribute.description: The decomposition_stages attribute identifies the number of stages of wavelet decompositions.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_block_size_x
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_block_size_x attribute provides the line dimension of a pixel block for on-board compression. If the instrument_compression_block_size_y attribute is not included, the block is assumed to be square.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_block_size_y
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_block_size_y attribute provides the sample dimension of a pixel block for on-board compression.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_blocks
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_blocks attribute provides the number of blocks used to spatially segment a data product prior to compression.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_color_mode
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_color_mode attribute specifies the color mode used during compression.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: TBD
TBD
TBD

attribute.title: instrument_compression_error_pixels
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_error_pixels attribute provides the number of pixels that are outside a valid DN range, after all decompression and post decompression processing has been completed

attribute.title: instrument_compression_mode
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_mode attribute identifies the method used for on-board compression of data. Note: For MPF, the modes were assigned to the corresponding inst_cmprs_names as follows: 1 JPEG DISCRETE COSINE TRANSFORM (DCT); HUFFMAN/QUALITY 2 JPEG DISCRETE COSINE TRANSFORM (DCT); HUFFMAN/RATIO 3 JPEG DISCRETE COSINE TRANSFORM (DCT); ARITHMETIC/QUALITY 4 JPEG DISCRETE COSINE TRANSFORM (DCT); ARITHMETIC/RATIO 5 JPEG DISCRETE COSINE TRANSFORM (DCT); HUFFMAN/QUALITY/LCT 6 JPEG DISCRETE COSINE TRANSFORM (DCT); HUFFMAN/RATIO/LCT 7 JPEG DISCRETE COSINE TRANSFORM (DCT); ARITHMETIC/QUALITY/LCT 8 JPEG DISCRETE COSINE TRANSFORM (DCT); ARITHMETIC/RATIO/LCT 9 RICE ADAPTIVE VARIABLE-LENGTH CODING (RICE)

attribute.title: instrument_compression_name
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_name attribute identifies the type of on-board compression used for data storage and transmission. Note: The instrument_compression_mode usually has a one-to-one correspondence with the instrument_compression_name.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_parameter
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_parameter attribute is a JPEG specific variable which specifies on-board compression determination by image quality or by compression factor, based on a selected on-board compression mode.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_quality
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_quality element is a JPEG specific variable which identifies the resultant or targeted image quality index for on-board data compression. Note: For MPF, if an odd IMP inst_cmprs_mode was used for on-board compression, the inst_cmprs_quality indicated the desired image quality index. If an odd inst_cmprs_mode was used, this indicates the resultant image quality used to reach the desired on-board compression factor.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_quantization_type
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_quantization_type attribute indicates the method of quantization used for the output of transform coders.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_rate
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_rate element provides the average number of bits needed to represent a pixel for an on-board compressed image.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_ratio
attribute.description: The inst_cmprs_ratio element provides the ratio of the size, in bytes, of the original uncompressed data file to its compressed form.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_segments
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_segments element identifies the number of segments into which the image was partitioned for the error containment purposes. For ICER compression, the data within each segment is compressed independently, so that data loss across segments is compartmentalized or contained across segments.

attribute.title: instrument_compression_type
attribute.description: The instrument_compression_type attribute identifies the type of on-board compression used for data storage and transmission. Note that inst_cmprs_name provides the full name of a compression algorithm (ex. Rice Adaptive Variable- Length Coding), whereas the inst_cmprs_type gives a simple indicator of the type of compression (ex. LOSSLESS). Note: For Cassini, the LOSSY compression scheme was Discrete Cosine Transform, the LOSSLESS compression scheme was RICE, and NOTCOMP meant no compression scheme was used.

attribute.title: quantization_table_id
attribute.description: The quantization_table_id attribute identifies the reference table used for quantization in the frequency domain for on-board transform compression. This name or code should be specific enough to allow the user of the data to have sufficient information to reference the quantization table used to compress the data. Standard values: - UNIFORM - UNK - VG2 - VG3

attribute.title: segment_first_line
attribute.description: The segment_first_line attribute identifies the line within a source image that corresponds to the first line of the compression segment identified by segment_number.

attribute.title: segment_first_sample
attribute.description: The segment_first_sample attribute identifies the sample within a source image that corresponds to the first sample of the compression segment identified by segment_number.

attribute.title: segment_lines
attribute.description: The segment_lines attribute identifies the total number of data instances along the vertical axis defined by the compression segment identified by segment_number.

attribute.title: segment_missing_pixels
attribute.description: The segment_missing_pixels attribute identifies the total number of missing pixels defined by the compression segment identified by segment_number.

attribute.title: segment_number
attribute.description: The segment_number attribute identifies which compression segment is described in the current Instrument_Compression_Segment class.

attribute.title: segment_quality
attribute.description: The segment_quality attribute identifies the quality level for the ICER compression segment identified by segment_number.

attribute.title: segment_samples
attribute.description: The segment_samples attribute identifies the total number of data instances along the horizontal axis defined by the compression segment identified by segment_number.

attribute.title: segment_status
attribute.description: The segment_status attribute provides a bit mask which provides the status of decoding for the compression segment identified by segment_number.

attribute.title: raw_count
attribute.description: The raw_count attribute provides the value of some parameter measured by a spacecraft or instrument sensor in the raw units reported by that sensor. The value may or may not be unitless, depending on what is being measured.

attribute.title: temperature_calibrated
attribute.description: The temperature_calibrated attribute provides the temperature, in the specified units, of some point on an instrument or other device.

attribute.title: temperature_raw
attribute.description: The temperature_raw attribute provides the raw, uncalibrated, temperature of some point on an instrument or other device.

attribute.title: name
attribute.description: The name attribute provides a word or combination of words by which the object is known.

attribute.title: expected_packets
attribute.description: The expected_packets attribute provides the total number of telemetry packets which constitute a complete data product, i.e., a data product without missing data.

attribute.title: missing_packet_flag
attribute.description: The missing_packet_flag attribute indicates whether or not there were telemetry packets that were expected but not received.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: All telemetry packets that were expected were received.
All telemetry packets that were expected were received.
Some telemetry packets that were expected were not received.
Some telemetry packets that were expected were not received.

attribute.title: packet_creation_date_time
attribute.description: The packet_creation_date_time attribute specifies the time, in standard UTC format, that data was packetized on board a spacecraft. This value is not always co-incident with the data acquisition time.

attribute.title: packet_creation_sclk
attribute.description: The packet_creation_sclk attribute specifies the value of the spacecraft clock at the time that data was packetized on board a spacecraft. This value is not always co-incident with the data acquisition time.

attribute.title: packet_map_mask
attribute.description: The packet_map_mask attribute is a binary or hexadecimal number identifying which of a data file's expected packets were actually received. The digits correspond positionally with the relative packet numbers of the data file. The bits are to be read left to right; i.e., the first (left-most) digit of the number corresponds to the first packet of the data file. A bit value of 1 indicates that the packet was received; a value of 0 indicates that it was not received.

attribute.title: received_packets
attribute.description: The received_packets attribute provides the total number of telemetry packets which constitute a reconstructed data product, cf. expected_packets.

attribute.title: pointing_model_name
attribute.description: The pointing_model_name attribute specifies which of several "pointing models" were used to transform the camera model based on updated pointing information. These updates are typically derived from mosaic seam corrections. This keyword and the associated Pointing_Model_Index classes define what the updated pointing information is, providing enough information to re-create the camera model from calibration data. If present, this keyword overrides the default pointing based on telemetry. The special value "NONE" shall be interpreted the same as if the keyword is absent (i.e. the default pointing model should be used). New model names can be created at any time; the models themselves should be described in a mission-specific ancillary file. See also the geom:solution_id attribute within the geom:Camera_Model_Parameters class.

attribute.title: pointing_model_solution_id
attribute.description: The pointing_model_solution_id attribute specifies the identifier of the pointing correction solution used to derive the model specified via the enclosing Pointing_Correction_Parameters class. This identifier should also appear in the pointing correction file referenced by the Data_Correction_File. If there is only one identifier in the correction file, then pointing_model_solution_id may be omitted. The pointing_model_solution_id attribute may be reused in the context of pointing corrections, although uniqueness is recommended. The pointing correction solution ID namespace is separate from the coordinate system namespace.

attribute.title: index_name
attribute.description: The index_name attribute supplies the formal name for the associated value in a group of related values.

attribute.title: index_value_real
attribute.description: The index_value_real attribute provides the real number value as named by the associated index_id or index_name.

attribute.title: product_producer_full_name
attribute.description: The product_producer_full_name attribute provides the complete name for a person and includes titles and suffixes.

attribute.title: product_producer_id
attribute.description: The product_producer_id attribute provides a short name or acronym identifying the organization or team which produced a product. Ex. "LRO_LROC_TEAM", "MIPL of JPL"

attribute.title: product_producer_institution_name
attribute.description: The product_producer_institution_name attribute identifies a university, research center, national space agency, or other institution associated with the production of a PDS archive. This is generally an institution associated with the Producer_Name. Ex. "Max Planck Institute", "NASA/Goddard Space Flight Center"

attribute.title: image_id
attribute.description: The image_id specifies an image and typically consists of a sequence of characters representing 1) a routinely occurring measure, such as revolution number, 2) a letter identifying the spacecraft, target, or camera, and 3) a representation of a count within the measure, such as picture number within a given revolution. NOTE: See the Imaging FDD for more detailed definition. Examples: Mariner 9 - LevanthalIdentifier - (orbit, camera, pic #, total # of pics in orbit) Viking Orbiter - (orbit #, sc, pic # (FSC/16)) Viking Lander - (sc, camera, mars doy, diode (filter), pic # for that day) Voyager - (pic # for encounter, FDS for cruise)

attribute.title: image_observation_type
attribute.description: The image_observation_type element identifies the type or purpose of an observation that may be associated with an image. Image observation types include limb, black sky, spacecraft calibration, or other image attribute that may be used for identification. Observation types should not include features, regions, or standard target names.

attribute.title: image_type
attribute.description: The image_type attribute specifies the type of image acquired. This may be used to describe characteristics that differentiate one group of images from another such as the nature of the data in the image file, the purpose for which the image was acquired, or the way in which it was acquired. This element is very similar to the older image_observation_type element, but is designed to resolve ambiguities in cases where missions utilize a naming convention for both specific images and more general observations, which consist of multiple images. In those cases, the latter may be described by the observation_type element.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: image
reference pixels

attribute.title: mesh_id
attribute.description: The mesh_id attribute specifies which terrain mesh this image should be automatically included in. This does not constrain which mesh(es) the image may be included in outside a pipeline environment.

attribute.title: mosaic_id
attribute.description: The mosaic_id attribute specifies which mosaic this image should be automatically included in. This does not constrain which mosaic(s) the image may be included in outside a pipeline environment.

attribute.title: stereo_match_id
attribute.description: The stereo_match_id attribute specifies which other image this image matches with for stereo processing. If used for a mission, the two images making up a stereo pair should share the same stereo_match_id value.

attribute.title: radiance_offset
attribute.description: The radiance_offset attribute specifies the constant value by which a stored radiance is added. Expressed as an equation as follows: true_radiance_value = radiance_offset + radiance_scaling_factor * stored_radiance value There are 3 types of radiometric corrections: Radiance-calibrated RDRs These "RAD" (and "RAL") RDRs have been scaled to absolute radiance units using either pre-flight radiometric calibration coefficients or calibration coefficients derived from in-flight observations of the calibration target. The units on these files are (W/m^2/sr/nm). Radiance factor-calibrated RDRs These "IOF" (and "IOL") RDRs are unitless but have values in the range of 0.0 to 1.0 (for example, average bright Mars soils exhibit I/F ~ 0.35 at 750 nm and I/F ~ 0.05 at 410 nm). Instrumentally-calibrated RDRs These "CCD" (and "CCL") RDRs have had no radiance scaling applied, so the units on these files are "corrected" DN.

attribute.title: radiance_scaling_factor
attribute.description: The radiance_scaling_factor specifies the constant value by which a stored radiance is multiplied. NOTE: Expressed as an equation: true_radiance_value = radiance_offset + radiance_scaling_factor * stored_radiance value There are 3 types of radiometric corrections: Radiance-calibrated RDRs These "RAD" (and "RAL") RDRs have been scaled to absolute radiance units using either pre-flight radiometric calibration coefficients or calibration coefficients derived from in-flight observations of the calibration target. The units on these files are (W/m^2/sr/nm). Radiance factor-calibrated RDRs These "IOF" (and "IOL") RDRs are unitless but have values in the range of 0.0 to 1.0 (for example, average bright Mars soils exhibit I/F ~ 0.35 at 750 nm and I/F ~ 0.05 at 410 nm). Instrumentally-calibrated RDRs These "CCD" (and "CCL") RDRs have had no radiance scaling applied, so the units on these files are "corrected" DN.

attribute.title: radiometric_correction_type
attribute.description: The radiometric_correction_type identifies the method used for radiometric correction.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Correction done by the ChemCam team

Correction done by MIPL (flat-field, exposure and temperature
          only)
No radiometric correction has been performed

attribute.title: software_host_name
attribute.description: The name of a computer on which a process was run.

attribute.title: software_user_id
attribute.description: A short identifier used to run a computer process.

attribute.title: description
attribute.description: The description attribute provides a statement, picture in words, or account that describes or is otherwise relevant to the object.

attribute.title: name
attribute.description: The name attribute provides a word or combination of words by which the object is known.

attribute.title: software_version_id
attribute.description: The software_version_id attribute provides the version of the software.

attribute.title: start_date_time
attribute.description: The start_date_time attribute provides the date and time appropriate to the beginning of the product being labeled.

attribute.title: stop_date_time
attribute.description: The stop_date_time attribute provides the date and time appropriate to the end of the product being labeled.

attribute.title: multi_image_radiance_factor
attribute.description: The multi_image_radiance_factor attribute specifies for a multi-input image (such as a mosaic), the overall multiplicative factor that was applied to each image as the mosaic was being assembled. Together with the multi_image_radiance_offset attribute, this specifies a simple linear adjustment of the form dn * factor + offset, that can be used for (limited) radiometric seam correction. Each pixel within a given input image receives the same correction. The order of images is as defined in the input list file (generally delivered along with the mosaic) or the input_product_id attribute. Applies to RDRs only, not EDRs. Note:: This correction is applied after radiometric correction, if any, performed on the inputs.

attribute.title: multi_image_radiance_offset
attribute.description: The multi_image_radiance_offset attribute specifies, for a multi-input image (such as a mosaic), the overall additive offset that was applied to each image as the mosaic was being assembled. Together with the multi_image_radiance_factor attribute, this specifies a simple linear adjustment of the form dn * factor + offset, that can be used for (limited) radiometric seam correction. Each pixel within a given input image receives the same correction. Input values of 0 are not adjusted. The order of images is as defined in the input list file (generally delivered along with the mosaic) or INPUT_PRODUCT_ID. Applies to RDRs only, not EDRs. NOTE: This correction is applied after radiometric correction, if any, performed on the inputs.

attribute.title: source_telemetry_sclk_start
attribute.description: The source_telemetry_sclk_start attribute specifies the value of the spacecraft clock (in seconds) at the creation time of the source product from which this product was derived. This differs from SPACECRAFT_CLOCK_START_COUNT, which is the time the instrument acquired the data.

attribute.title: source_telemetry_start_time
attribute.description: The source_telemetry_start_time attribute specifies the creation time of the source product from which this product was derived. It is the same as value of the source_telemetry_sclk_start attribute converted to Spacecraft Event Time (SCET).

attribute.title: stereo_baseline
attribute.description: The stereo_baseline attribute specifies the separation between the two cameras used for processing of the stereo image.
attribute.unitId: AU, Angstrom, cm, km, m, micrometer, mm, nm

attribute.title: command_source_id
attribute.description: The command_source_id attribute specifies the flight software element that was the source of a particular command.

attribute.title: first_line
attribute.description: The first_line attribute indicates the line within a source image that corresponds to the first line in a sub-image.

attribute.title: first_sample
attribute.description: The first_sample attribute indicates the sample within a source image that corresponds to the first sample in a sub-image.

attribute.title: lines
attribute.description: The lines element indicates the total number of data instances along the vertical axis of an image. Note: In PDS label convention, the number of lines is stored in a 32-bit integer field. The minimum value of 0 indicates no data received.

attribute.title: samples
attribute.description: The samples attribute indicates the number of picture elements along the horizontal axis of an image or sub-image.

attribute.title: subframe_type
attribute.description: The subframe_type attribute specifies the method of subframing performed on the image. NONE indicates no subframing requested. SW_ONLY indicates software processing HW_COND specifies hardware only if compatible. HW_SW indicates the of hardware then software. SUBFRM_SUN specifies the subframe around the sun.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: indicates software processing
specifies hardware only if compatible
indicates the of hardware then software
specifies the subframe around the sun.

attribute.title: description
attribute.description: The description attribute provides a statement, picture in words, or account that describes or is otherwise relevant to the object.

attribute.title: name
attribute.description: The name attribute provides a word or combination of words by which the object is known.

attribute.title: download_priority
attribute.description: The download_priority attribute specifies which data to download based on order of importance.

attribute.title: earth_received_start_date_time
attribute.description: The earth_received_start_date_time attribute provides the earliest time at which any component telemetry data for a particular product was received.

attribute.title: earth_received_stop_date_time
attribute.description: The earth_received_stop_date_time attribute provides the latest time at which any component telemetry data for a particular product was received.

attribute.title: error_pixel_line
attribute.description: The error_pixel_line attribute specifies the line number in the image where an error occurred.

attribute.title: error_pixel_sample
attribute.description: The error_pixel_sample attribute specifies the sample number in the image where an error occurred.

attribute.title: product_completion_status
attribute.description: The product_completion_status attribute specifies the completion status of a product, specifying for example, if all portions have been downlinked and received correctly, if it is a partial product, or if it contains transmission errors. The specific valid values may be mission-dependent.

attribute.title: surface_gravity
attribute.description: The surface_gravity attribute specifies the acceleration of gravity (magnitude, not direction)

attribute.title: telemetry_application_id
attribute.description: The telemetry_application_id attribute identifies the process, or source, which created the data. This can include information such as an identification of the instrument which generated the telemetry stream, its operating mode at the time of data acquisition, and any onboard compression of the data.

attribute.title: telemetry_application_name
attribute.description: The telemetry_application_name attribute provides the name associated with the source or process which created the data.

attribute.title: telemetry_application_subtype_id
attribute.description: The telemetry_application_subtype_id attribute provides further distinction (i.e., greater specificity) among telemetry_application_id types.

attribute.title: telemetry_downlink_protocol_type
attribute.description: The telemetry_downlink_protocol_type attribute specifies the protocol used by the source of a telemetry stream for creating telemetry data products.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Standard Formatted Data Unit; used by Cassini, Phoenix, Insight
Data Product file delivery protocol; used by MER and MSL.
CCSDS File Delivery Protocol; used by MRO, Juno, Insight

attribute.title: telemetry_image_data_size
attribute.description: The image_data_size specifies the size of an image data item..

attribute.title: telemetry_provider_id
attribute.description: The telemetry_provider_id attribute identifies the organization or subsystem that supplied the telemetry data product to the producer of the raw (EDR) PDS data product. This is typically (but not always) the organization responsible for reassembling packetized data into a single product.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Mission data Processing and Control System (used by MSL)
Front end Data Manager (used by JUNO and MRO)
Test Telemetry And Command Subsystem

The DSN's Telemetry Data (or Delivery) System (alternately, "Telemetry Data
          Staging")

attribute.title: mission_phase_name
attribute.description: The mission_phase_name identifies a time period within the mission.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: The pre-launch mission phase is from the beginning of the mission through time of launch.
The launch mission phase is from the time of launch through the time of escape from Earth's orbit.
The cruise mission phase is from the time of escape from Earth's orbit through the time of entry into Mars' orbit.
The EDL mission phase is from the time of entry into Mars' orbit through descent and landing on the surface.
The primary mission phase is from the time of landing on Mars through one Mars year of operations.
The extended mission phase covers the time of mission operations following the end of the primary mission.

attribute.title: observation_id
attribute.description: The observation_id uniquely identifies an Insight science observation.

attribute.title: product_type
attribute.description: The product_type identifies a group of data products within a collection that have some property in common, such as processing level, resolution, or instrument-specific setting. Examples: "EDR", "RDR", "C1-MIDR", "Housekeeping", "Raw Counts", "Targeted RDR", "Gamma Ray Spectra".

attribute.title: release_number
attribute.description: Release_number is the number of a scheduled release of InSight data from PDS. The first Insight data release is Release 1. The release_number for a given product is always the first release in which it appears, and does not change if the product is revised later.

attribute.title: sequence_id
attribute.description: The sequence_id identifies the Insight planning sequence associated with a science product.

attribute.title: sequence_version_id
attribute.description: The sequence_version_id identifies the version of an Insight planning sequence associated with a science product.

attribute.title: software_name
attribute.description: Software_name identifies the processing software used to generate a data product.

attribute.title: software_version_id
attribute.description: Software_version_id identifies the version of the processing software used to generate a data product.

attribute.title: sol_number
attribute.description: Sol_number is the number of the Mars day on which an observation was acquired. Landing day is Sol 0.

attribute.title: spacecraft_clock_start_count
attribute.description: The spacecraft_clock_start_count is the value of the spacecraft clock at the beginning of an observation.

attribute.title: spacecraft_clock_stop_count
attribute.description: The spacecraft_clock_stop_count is the value of the spacecraft clock at the end of an observation.

attribute.title: start_local_mean_solar_time
attribute.description: Start_local_mean_solar_time is the local mean solar time, as defined in the main PDS4 data dictionary, at the beginning of an observation.

attribute.title: start_sol_number
attribute.description: Start_sol_number is the number of the Mars day on which a multiple-day observation was begun. Landing day is Sol 0.

attribute.title: start_solar_longitude

attribute.title: center_wavelength
attribute.description: The center_wavelength attribute provides the wavelength or frequency describing the center of a bin along the band axis of a spectral qube. When describing data from a spectrometer, the value corresponds to the peak of the response function for a particular detector and/or grating position.
attribute.unitId: AU, Angstrom, cm, km, m, micrometer, mm, nm

attribute.title: detector_number
attribute.description: The detector_number attribute provides the spectrometer detector number corresponding to a band of a spectral qube. Detector numbers are usually assigned consecutively from 1, in order of increasing wavelength.

attribute.title: filter_number
attribute.description: The filter_number attribute of a spectral qube describes the physical location of a band (identified by the band_number) in a detector array. Filter 1 is on the leading edge of the array.

attribute.title: grating_position
attribute.description: The grating_position attribute of a spectral qube describes the grating position which corresponds to the band. Grating positions are usually assigned consecutively from 0, and increasing position causes increasing wavelength for each detector.

attribute.title: original_band
attribute.description: The original_band attribute of a spectral qube provides the sequence of band numbers in the qube relative to some original qube. In the original qube, the values are just consecutive integers beginning with 1. In a qube which contains a subset of the bands in the original qube, the values are the original sequence numbers from that qube.

attribute.title: scaling_factor
attribute.description: The scaling_factor attribute is the scaling factor to be applied to each stored value in order to recover an original  value. The observed value (Ov) is calculated from the stored value (Sv) thus: Ov = (Sv * scaling_factor) + value_offset. The default value is 1.

attribute.title: standard_deviation
attribute.description: The standard_deviation attribute provides the standard deviation of values in the associated object; empty and Special_Constants values are excluded.

attribute.title: value_offset
attribute.description: The value_offset attribute is the offset to be applied to each stored value in order to recover an original  value. The observed value (Ov) is calculated from the stored value (Sv) thus: Ov = (Sv * scaling_factor) + value_offset. The default value is 0.

attribute.title: author_list
attribute.description: The author_list attribute provides a list of people to be cited as the authors of the asssociated product. Lists are constructed with last names first and first and middle names and/or initials following. Initials are terminated by periods and delimited by single spaces. Suffixes (if applicable) follow everything else, after a final comma. Hyphenated names may be reduced to initials as "J.-P." Each person's full name is separated from the next by a semi-colon. There is no "and" before the last name. If there is no author list, editor_list must be present and non-null.

attribute.title: archive_status
attribute.description: The ARCHIVE_STATUS attribute indicates the stage to which a data set has progressed in the archiving process, from IN QUEUE through ARCHIVED. It can also take on the values SUPERSEDED or SAFED, which indicate that the data set is not part of the active archive. ACCUMULATING can be appended to some values to indicate that the data set is incomplete and/or that not all components have reached the stage given by the root value; ACCUMULATING would be used, for example, when the archive is being delivered incrementally, as from a mission that lasts many months or years.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Archive status of the PDS3 data set is ARCHIVED (passed peer review with all liens resolved. Available through the Data Set Catalog and at NSSDC).

Archive status of the PDS3 data set is ARCHIVED_ACCUMULATING (some parts of the data set are ARCHIVED, but other parts are in earlier stages of the archiving process and/or have not yet been delivered to PDS; use with caution).
Archive status of the PDS3 data set is IN_LIEN_RESOLUTION (peer review completed; liens are in the process of being resolved; use with caution).

Archive status of the PDS3 data set is IN_LIEN_RESOLUTION_ACCUMULATING (some parts of the data set are IN LIEN RESOLUTION, but other parts are in earlier stages of the archiving process and/or have not yet been delivered to PDS; use with caution).
Archive status of the PDS3 data set is IN_PEER_REVIEW (under peer review at the curation node but evaluation is not complete; use with caution).

Archive status of the PDS3 data set is IN_PEER_REVIEW_ACCUMULATING (some parts of the data set are IN PEER REVIEW, but other parts are in earlier stages of the archiving process and/or have not yet been delivered to PDS; use with caution).
Archive status of the PDS3 data set is IN_QUEUE (received at the curation node but no action has been taken by the curation node; use with caution).
Archive status of the PDS3 data set is IN_QUEUE_ACCUMULATING (some parts of the data set are IN QUEUE, but other parts have not yet been delivered to PDS; use with caution).

Archive status of the PDS3 data set is LOCALLY_ARCHIVED (passed peer review with all liens resolved; considered archived by the curation node but awaiting completion of the standard archiving process; possible TBD items include the arrival of the archive volume at NSSDC and ingestion of catalog information into the Data Set Catalog).

Archive status of the PDS3 data set is LOCALLY_ARCHIVED_ACCUMULATING (some parts of the data set are LOCALLY ARCHIVED, but other parts are in earlier stages of the archiving process and/or have not yet been delivered to PDS; use with caution).
Archive status of the PDS3 data set is PRE_PEER_REVIEW (being prepared for peer review under the direction of the  curation node; use with caution).'

Archive status of the PDS3 data set is PRE_PEER_REVIEW_ACCUMULATING (some parts of the data set are in PRE PEER REVIEW, but other parts are IN QUEUE and/or have not yet been delivered to PDS; use with caution).
Archive status of the PDS3 data set is SAFED (the data set has been received by the PDS with no evaluation; data will not be formally archived).

Archive status of the PDS3 data set is SUPERSEDED (this data set has been replaced by a newer version, implying that the data set is not to be used unless the requester has specific reasons; when a data set has been superseded the Engineering Node, will notify NSSDC that their databases need to be updated to advise users of the new status and the location of the replacement data set).

attribute.title: citation_text
attribute.description: The citation_text attribute provides a character string containing a literature or other citation in sufficient detail that the material  could be located in PDS or elsewhere.

attribute.title: confidence_level_note
attribute.description: The confidence_level_note attribute is a text field which characterizes the reliability of data within a data set or the reliability of a particular programming algorithm or software component. Essentially, this note discusses the level of confidence in the accuracy of the data or in the ability of the software to produce accurate results.

attribute.title: data_set_desc
attribute.description: The data_set_desc attribute describes the content and type of a data set and provides information required to use the data (such as binning information).

attribute.title: data_set_id
attribute.description: The data set id provides a formal name used to refer to a data set.

attribute.title: data_set_name
attribute.description: The data_set_name attribute provides the full name given to a data set or a data product. The data_set_name typically identifies the instrument that acquired the data of that instrument Example value data_set_id. Note This attribute is defined in the AMMOS Magellan catalog as an alias for file_name to provide backward compatibility

attribute.title: data_set_release_date
attribute.description: The data_set_release_date attribute provides the date when a data set is released by the data producer for archive or publication. In many systems this represents the end of a proprietary or validation period. Formation rule In AMMOS identify the date at which a product may be released to the general public from proprietary access. AMMOS-related systems should apply this attribute only to proprietary data.

attribute.title: data_set_terse_desc
attribute.description: A one line description of the data set

attribute.title: producer_full_name
attribute.description: The producer_full_name attribute provides the full_name of the individual mainly responsible for the production of the data set. This individual does not have to be registered with the PDS.

attribute.title: start_date_time
attribute.description: The start_date_time attribute provides the date and time at the beginning of the data set.

attribute.title: start_time
attribute.description: The start_time attribute provides the date and time of the beginning of an event or observation (whether it be a spacecraft, ground-based, or system event) in UTC.

attribute.title: stop_date_time
attribute.description: The stop_date_time attribute provides the date and time at the end of the data set.

attribute.title: stop_time
attribute.description: The stop_time element provides the date and time of the end of an observation or event (whether it be a spacecraft, ground-based, or system event) in UTC.

attribute.title: bit_string
attribute.description: The bit string attribute is a sequence of digital bits. It is the content of a digital object.

attribute.title: discipline_name
attribute.description: The discipline_name attribute describes the observing discipline (as opposed to a PDS Discipline Node Name, though the concepts and values are similar). Some of these values are, with respect to the PDS Nodes, inter-disciplinary and should be used when they are applicable in perference to the more restrictive values.
